{\qc
Praise for {\i
What the Dormouse Said}}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"At the core of {\i
Dormouse} lies a valid and original historical point.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
The New York Times}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"A convincing case\uc3\u8230.... This makes entertaining reading.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
The New York Times}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Evocative\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
Newsweek}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Fascinating\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
Computerworld}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Fascinating\uc3\u8230...Markoff is a wonderful writer and storyteller, and he effortlessly weaves together the stories of the main cast of characters. The individuals had the most unusual knack for crossing paths, and Markoff\uc1\u8217's ability to show these sometimes tangential\uc2\u8212--but always important\uc2\u8212--relationships, without losing the thread of the story, is impressive.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
The Christian Science Monitor}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Nobody writes about computer technology better than Markoff, who gives us insights into the people, history and societal pressures that drive breakthroughs and new developments. Here he convincingly traces the birth of personal computing to the counterculture ethos of the Bay Area in the \uc1\u8217'60s.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
San Jose Mercury News}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Shows how almost every feature of today\uc1\u8217's home computers\uc3\u8230...can be traced to two Stanford research facilities that were completely immersed in the counterculture\uc3\u8230.... The combustive combination of radical politics and technological ambition is laid out so convincingly, in fact, that it\uc1\u8217's mildly disappointing when, in the closing pages, Markoff attaches momentous significance to a confrontation between the freewheeling Californian computer culture and a young Bill Gates only to bring the story to an abrupt halt. Hopefully, he\uc1\u8217's already started work on the sequel.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
Publishers Weekly} (starred review) }}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"A lively prehistory of Silicon Valley and its brilliant denizens of yore\uc3\u8230.... Technogeeks will know much of this history already, but Markoff does a fine job of distilling it here while pointing out how much bleaker the world might be if the pioneers had just said no.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
Kirkus Reviews}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Striking\uc3\u8230.... a fine job of recording the history of that exceptional time. Both informative and entertaining, this book should appeal to a broad audience of technology readers.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--{\i
Library Journal}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Thanks to the cunning of history and the wondrous strangeness of Northern California, the utopian counterculture, psychedelic drugs, military hardware and antimilitary software were tangled together inextricably in the prehistory of the personal computer. Full of interesting details about weird but not arbitrary connections, John Markoff\uc1\u8217's book tells one of the oddest\uc2\u8212--because truest\uc2\u8212--of California tales and thereby helps illuminate the still unsettled legacy of the Sixties.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--Todd Gitlin, author of {\i
Media Unlimited} and {\i
The Sixties: Years of Hope, Days of Rage}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"It is easy to see how the personal computer has shaped contemporary culture. But how did contemporary culture shape the emergence of the personal computer? In this innovative, lively narrative, veteran technology reporter and cultural critic John Markoff demonstrates how the values and obsessions of the 1960s, especially as centered in the San Francisco Bay Area, created the environment for the emergence of the personal computer as social tool and cultural catalyst.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--Kevin Starr, author of {\i
Coast of Dreams: California on the Edge, 1990\uc1\u8211-2003}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"John Markoff \uc1\u8217's wonderful recounting of the origins of personal computerdom makes a mind-blowing case that our current silicon marvels were inspired by the psychedelic-tinged, revolution-minded spirit of the Sixties. It\uc1\u8217's a total turn-on.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--Steven Levy, author of {\i
Hackers, Crypto}, and {\i
Insanely Great}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Beautifully written, {\i
What the Dormouse Said} does that important job of placing in a historical context the development of modern computer technology. It tells us not only what happened, but why. These people changed our world as much as any group ever and now I understand not only how it came to be but also why it was probably inevitable.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--Robert X. Cringely, author of {\i
Accidental Empires} and host of the PBS series {\i
Triumph of the Nerds}}}
{\line }

{\line }
{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"Reviled and demonized, then trivialized by the official culture it so exuberantly opposed, the counterculture of the 1960s nevertheless remains the 2000-pound gorilla in the china closet of recent American history. With elegance and efficiency, {\i
What The Dormouse Said} charts one of the most important and overlooked songlines from that mind-expanding moment. Tune in, turn on, boot up!\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
{\qr
\uc2\u8212--Jay Stevens, author of {\i
Storming Heaven: LSD and the America Dream} and {\i
Burning Down the House}}}
