Lying west of Stanford are the Santa Cruz Mountains, which are frequently shrouded in fog and covered with a redwood forest that, though spotty, still wanders down to the coast in places. To reach the ocean, it was necessary only to drive past the university out Sand Hill Road to La Honda Road, a winding artery that makes its way from the elite Woodside mansions into a more rustic and rugged world, peopled by a mix of urban refugees thrown together with a rural community of artists, farmers, and bohemians.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Anyone driving to the coast in August 1966 would have been surprised to see a large banner reading \uc1\u8220"Welcome Beatles!\uc1\u8221" while passing through the mountain hamlet of La Honda. The British rock group was in the midst of a triumphant American concert tour and was about to play before thousands of screaming teenagers in San Francisco. The possibility that the Fab Four might make an unlikely detour to this out-of-the-way community created a brief local sensation in the Bay Area. But it turned out to be just a stunt pulled by Ken Kesey\uc1\u8217's Merry Pranksters, one perfectly suited to the times, which were rapidly beginning to tumble out of control. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Driving down La Honda Road on the way to the coast, at milepost 13.57, just a mile and half from the summit, a visitor would pass a once-nondescript cottage that had been painted with striking psychedelic swirls. Out front, facing La Honda Road, was a huge yinyang symbol. The cottage was the home of Jim Warren, a chunky math professor at the College of Notre Dame, a small Catholic girls\uc1\u8217' school located in Belmont.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
More than a decade later, Warren emerged as one of the central figures in defining the tone of the personal-computer industry when he created the first West Coast Computer Faire in 1977, a show that became a mecca for computer hobbyists. But long before that, he was emblematic of the cultural, political, and technological forces colliding over the hill from his cottage.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Growing up in San Antonio, Texas, Warren felt like an outsider. His parents had been largely immune to the racism that was endemic in the South in the 1940s and 1950s, and as a young child he had two close friends in his neighborhood who firmly set him apart. One was a black kid who was the son of a woman who worked as a servant, and the other was a Jew. In high school, he spent his time with a dissolute group of blacks who had formed a rhythm-and-blues band and wound up playing rock and roll even before there was such a thing.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
In college, he obtained a teaching credential and then took a job teaching math in San Antonio. Several years later, the launch of Sputnik had supercharged the scientific and educational communities in the United States, and Warren was given the opportunity to take a year off from teaching funded by the National Science Foundation, to study for his master\uc1\u8217's degree in Austin. There he ran into his first computer\uc2\u8212--like Tesler\uc1\u8217's, an IBM 650\uc2\u8212--and threw himself into his studies. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
While he was back in school, he traveled with a bohemian crowd on the fringes of the culture that defined the University of Texas campus. His friends included a group of archaeology and anthropology students who were frequently off on field trips to excavate Native American ruins. In the course of their work, they had discovered peyote, which was perfectly legal in some places at the time. Warren was avowedly straight, but he found himself running errands on his trips back to San Antonio. At the time he didn\uc1\u8217't even drink beer, but he would go to Hogan\uc1\u8217's Cactus Gardens and pick up three dollars\uc1\u8217' worth of peyote buds for his friends. One member of the group was a braless and overweight young woman named Janis Joplin, who made no pretense of fitting in and shocked the good students of Texas by smooching with her girlfriend in the cafeteria.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
After getting his master\uc1\u8217's, he went back for what turned out to be his final year as a teacher in San Antonio. He pulled together a class of bright kids and began teaching them what was then being called \uc1\u8220"modern math\uc1\u8221": learning underlying principles rather than rote memorization. On the first day, he stood up in front of the class and said, \uc1\u8220"This is your math book,\uc1\u8221" and then took it, walked to the door, tossed it into the hallway, and came back to the front of the class and said, \uc1\u8220"Now we\uc1\u8217're going to learn some REAL math.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He loved teaching, but his sense of alienation from Texas was increasing. In the end there was nothing left about the state he could stand. He knew he had to leave, but for where? The answer came from a friend, who told him quietly, \uc1\u8220"You might like California.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He decided to buy a truck big enough to haul his belongings and in the summer of 1964 set out for San Jose. Upon arriving, his immediate reaction was \uc1\u8220"I\uc1\u8217'm home, I\uc1\u8217'm finally home.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He couldn\uc1\u8217't believe his luck. Hedonism and experimentation were in full swing, and he found himself in a place where the girls actually admitted they liked sex. Warren quickly found a job in Mountain View, which was then a working-class community in the heart of what would become Silicon Valley. It soon became clear, however, that his heart was no longer in teaching junior high school kids, who had all come to seem hormonally unbalanced. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
In fact, he was twenty-seven years old, and he was girl crazy. His interests came to encompass other exciting things\uc2\u8212--in particular, the political crisis that was developing across the bay at the University of California. The Free Speech Movement pitted student activists with a new set of values against an old educational guard. For Warren, the events unfolding were in sync with his own escape from a claustrophobic and reactionary climate in Texas. He quickly began to identify with the student and antiwar groups.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
However, the politics of the emerging American left were far from straightforward. Indeed, the various cultural and political factions around the Bay Area and on the Midpeninsula often spent as much time confronting one another as they did society\uc1\u8217's more conservative institutions. As he complained to his friends, \uc1\u8220"The problem with the right is they don\uc1\u8217't have any leaders; the problem with the left is that they have too many leaders.\uc1\u8221"{\super
{\ul
4}}}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He began to gravitate toward an increasingly sybaritic lifestyle. His first girlfriend introduced him to nudism, and they were soon regulars at the Lupine Nature Preserve, a nudist colony in the Santa Cruz Mountains. In the mountains he also stumbled across the Merry Pranksters.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Before buying his cottage on La Honda Road, he had rented another place near La Honda. Standing in the new house one morning attempting to deal with the fact that the squatters he found upon moving in were taking their time leaving, he was startled when the door abruptly opened and in walked Neal Cassady, the legendary Beat-era figure who had been the thinly disguised protagonist of Jack Kerouac\uc1\u8217's novel {\i
On the Road} and who was now driving the Pranksters\uc1\u8217' bus, trailed by a band of hangers-on. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Without bothering to introduce himself, Cassady and his followers began to search the house while speed-rapping \uc1\u8220"Got the mash, where\uc1\u8217's my stash?\uc1\u8221" which made no sense at all to Warren. The weird scene ended just as abruptly when the entire group headed for the door and piled into a car heading off up La Honda Road, tires screeching.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Warren moved in shortly before Kesey\uc1\u8217's 1965 drug bust. He knew it was in the offing when his girlfriend stumbled across two gentlemen with coats, ties, and binoculars as she walked along the trail behind Kesey\uc1\u8217's home.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He found another job and began making the daily commute from the mountains to Belmont, where he was the chairman of the math department at the all-women\uc1\u8217's college. The sisters of Notre Dame were a relatively liberal Catholic religious order, with a conservative board of trustees. The young women were away from home for the first time, and Warren saw that they had come from repressed families and were enjoying their relative freedom.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
With a booming voice and a raconteur\uc1\u8217's style, Warren was a popular teacher. It was a calling that fit the values his father had instilled in him early: It was important to give something back to society. However, over the next two years he found he was increasingly pulled in three conflicting directions. In addition to his professional role, which was still linked to the National Science Foundation\uc1\u8217's attempts to increase the quality of math education, there was the self-indulgent, increasingly hippie world of the Santa Cruz Mountains, as well as the growing intensity of the antiwar demonstrations in Berkeley.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
All of these forces were converging in 1966. Although he had been a teetotaler, 1966 was also the year that the psychedelic movement swept him up. With his girlfriend, who was part of the Berkeley academic scene, Warren visited an archaeological dig in Sonoma County, where he met a young man who sold him LSD.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He told himself, na\uc1\u239ively as it turned out, \uc1\u8220"I\uc1\u8217'll never have a chance to buy this again,\uc1\u8221" and then put the tablets away.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Shortly after that, in his travels in the Berkeley antiwar scene, he met an odd fellow who was a carpenter and a Mensa member. At his house one afternoon, the man offered Warren a joint.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"I\uc1\u8217've never tried this before,\uc1\u8221" Warren admitted, adding, \uc1\u8220"I\uc1\u8217've heard it makes you crazy, and besides, I don\uc1\u8217't smoke.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
His new friend assured him that it wasn\uc1\u8217't a big deal. In a ritual that was being repeated countless times around the country that year, he put rock music on his stereo and showed Warren how to turn on.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"He was already high, and I kept saying, \uc1\u8216'I don\uc1\u8217't feel anything.\uc1\u8217'\uc1\u8221" But then Warren found himself inexplicably pacing back and forth in his new friend\uc1\u8217's living room. They went to the kitchen, the friend offered Warren a bite of cantaloupe, and all of a sudden Warren felt as if his head were exploding. \uc1\u8220"I\uc1\u8217've never heard music like that before,\uc1\u8221" he told the carpenter. The life of the chairman of a college math department was taking a radical turn.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Two of his friends from the Lupine nudist colony told him about a secret beach just down the road from Warren\uc1\u8217's cabin in a cove north of San Gregorio State Beach. It was clothing-optional, and one hot spring afternoon he decided to drive down and check things out. He had a wonderful afternoon, strolling along the almost two miles of hidden sand, chatting with couples and families, all in various stages of undress. At the end of the day as he sauntered home, he began to invite people to stop in La Honda, pick up food for a barbecue, and come by his cottage on their way home.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
When the beachgoers arrived, they ranged from protohippies to IBM engineers, mixed with a smattering of academics. Soon there was a crowd of twenty-five to thirty people making dinner and getting acquainted, and when two of them asked if they could shower to wash off the sand from the beach, Warren thought nothing of it.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Until they returned from the shower without their clothes on.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Warren thought about it for a moment and then, with his characteristic enthusiasm, said, \uc1\u8220"Wow!\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Nobody else seemed to mind, and pretty soon clothing was coming off everywhere in the house and the garden.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
It wasn\uc1\u8217't a swinging scene or an orgy\uc2\u8212--that was already happening elsewhere in the Bay Area. And it wasn\uc1\u8217't the Sexual Freedom League that Warren later dabbled in but found to be oddly repressive in a mirror image to the Texas that he\uc1\u8217'd left behind: You {\i
had} to be naked and you {\i
had} to have sex. Rather, Warren\uc1\u8217's home became a center of the emerging California counterculture\uc2\u8212--he saw it as rejecting the tight-ass mainstream world and a focal point for some kind of vibrant alternative community. A whole range of worlds seemed to intersect in the parties at his mountain cabin: hippies, academics, rock and rollers, and people from the nude beach scene. For Warren it fulfilled a deeply felt need. He was single with no family and divorced parents. He didn\uc1\u8217't want to get married, but he was looking for something, and this felt like community. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Throughout 1966 and into the next year, the parties continued to grow until several hundred people were attending. They became the stuff of national and even worldwide press coverage. At one point, a BBC crew showed up to film a discreet, backlit scene as part of a documentary on the \uc1\u8220"Now\uc1\u8221" generation.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Then the {\i
San Francisco Chronicle} ran a front-page, above-the-fold article that described an unnamed professor who was throwing nude parties in the Santa Cruz Mountains. By then, it was inevitable that the straitlaced religious school would have heard rumors about the activities of its math department chair. He was hardly being secretive about the \uc1\u8220"really groovy\uc1\u8221" parties, and word eventually got to the students. With the campus inflamed, the president of the college called him in and said, \uc1\u8220"Well, is this true?\uc1\u8221" He responded, \uc1\u8220"Uh, yes.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
And she said, \uc1\u8220"Well, Professor Warren, you\uc1\u8217're an excellent professor, we\uc1\u8217're delighted to have you chair the math department, but I think you\uc1\u8217'll have to agree that having nude parties is rather incompatible with the philosophy of a Catholic girls\uc1\u8217' school.\uc1\u8221" Warren allowed that that was almost certainly true, and he asked the president if she would like him to resign. Without pausing, she said, \uc1\u8220"We would appreciate it very much.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Losing his job left Warren in a quandary, but not for long. All around Stanford University a cauldron of political activism, alternative community, and radical education experiments was boiling. Off campus, the Free University was attempting to encompass every diverse tendency from candle making to Maoism. On campus, student activists had created new organizations in an effort to force the university to loosen up and permit interdepartmental education. There was the Stanford Workshop on Political and Social Issues (SWOPSI) and the Stanford Center for Innovation and Research in Education (SCIRE).}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Warren\uc1\u8217's interest in Utopian communities drew him into the Free University, where amid the chaos of political radicals and hippies he proved to be a natural moderate. He was older than many of the participants and he had already demonstrated that he was a good administrator. He became chair of the group, but since it was a militant volunteer organization in which salaries weren\uc1\u8217't paid, he was forced to seek some means of support.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He set out to look for a job that wouldn\uc1\u8217't interfere with his real calling, which was to do the \uc1\u8220"shit work\uc1\u8221" to keep the Free U running. One of the alternative school\uc1\u8217's veterans was a researcher at the Stanford Medical Center, and he suggested that Warren come over and take a job as a computer programmer. Computers were increasingly being used in data collection and analysis in the medical school\uc1\u8217's research projects.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
It was perfect: Programmers were paid relatively well, and the hours were notoriously flexible. There was just one small problem. His experience writing software was limited to a prehistoric IBM computer he had programmed in assembly language.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"No problem,\uc1\u8221" the researcher assured him. \uc1\u8220"You\uc1\u8217'll pick it up.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
And Warren did. He was handed the manuals for a Digital PDP-8, a minicomputer that had eight kilobytes of memory and a magnetic-tape storage system. At the time, PDP-8s were flooding into the Bay Area, where they were being used for industrial process control. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
One of the first Free U regulars Warren met was Larry Tesler, who had closed down his independent programming business and taken a job at SAIL. By now, the Free University was speaking to a growing movement of people who were frustrated with the mainstream university system, which seemed to be increasingly in the thrall of the military-industrial complex. Thousands were attracted to the idea of education beyond the walls of the traditional classroom, and both Tesler and Warren became committed participants, with Warren serving at one point as chairman and Tesler as treasurer.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
In the evenings, the two frequently worked at the Free University store on El Camino Real, producing the Free University newspaper in the back room with one of the ubiquitous IBM Selectric typewriters. The machines, with their distinctive bouncing ball, were not just the gold standard for the corporate office world. Used Selectrics were highly prized by community and political groups because they made it possible to inexpensively produce reasonably acceptable-appearing pamphlets, newspapers, and propaganda. With scissors, X-Acto knives, and pots of glue, the two men painstakingly produced the Free U literature.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
One evening, Tesler grew frustrated with the slow pace of the work, turned to Warren, and said, \uc1\u8220"You know, Jim, this is really ridiculous. We have these big computer monitors at the AI lab, and we could really just display these pages up on the screen, and you could just cut and paste right in the screen, and we wouldn\uc1\u8217't have to do this stuff anymore.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Warren thought that this was a great idea and, after pondering the suggestion for a moment, asked, \uc1\u8220"Well, how would you get it onto paper after that?\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
That stopped Tesler\uc1\u8217's reverie. \uc1\u8220"I haven\uc1\u8217't figured that out yet,\uc1\u8221" he replied.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
It didn\uc1\u8217't immediately matter, and though it would take several years to bear fruit, the idea for interactive page layout was now firmly etched in Tesler\uc1\u8217's mind. }
