{\line }{\line }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Throughout his adventures and travails, one thing held reasonably constant: Moore had come to believe that money was the root of evil. \uc1\u8220"Due to money, we live by proxy,\uc1\u8221" he wrote. \uc1\u8220"Our life is abstracted from us by the coin we exchange.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
The evils of money might have remained his personal political obsession if Stewart Brand hadn\uc1\u8217't been suffering through deep bouts of depression and plunging into a nervous breakdown. The {\i
Whole Earth Catalog} was a runaway success by 1971, after two years of increasingly popular publications. But Brand was barely holding it together emotionally. His marriage to Lois Jennings, the Native American woman he had fallen in love with after leaving the army, was beginning to crumble. There was tremendous pressure to make each new {\i
Catalog} bigger and twice as impressive as the last, and the effort was beginning to overwhelm Brand. He had never had a break and found he had no idea how to take a vacation. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
It seemed that things were starting to close in, and he began to feel agoraphobic. One evening, he went to see {\i
The Swimmer}, a film based on a John Cheever story in which Burt Lancaster steadily goes mad as his world collapses. The movie shook Brand viscerally. He went back to the trailer where he was living on Alpine Road behind Stanford, thinking, {\i
People can really lose it,} and then it occurred to him that maybe he was losing it, too. He kept up appearances, putting out the last {\i
Catalog,} but began to contemplate suicide. In the end he went to several therapists, who helped him sort things out. He realized he was clinically depressed. He thought about the people around him for whom psychedelics had become an all-purpose cure and determined he wasn\uc1\u8217't going to use drugs as a crutch. Instead, he decided to get rid of things: first his marriage, and then the {\i
Catalog}. With its staff, he arranged to throw a {\i
Whole Earth Catalog} \uc1\u8220"Demise Party.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Brand had gotten to know Frank Oppenheimer, the founder of the Exploratorium science museum at the Palace of Fine Arts in the San Francisco Marina district, when he had helped Oppenheimer think through some of the museum\uc1\u8217's plans as it was being developed. So he decided to throw a party with a special twist. The {\i
Whole Earth Catalog} rented the museum\uc1\u8217's building for an evening, and as a surprise Brand brought along twenty thousand dollars in cash in an inch-thick stack of hundred-dollar bills with the idea that, because he had started the {\i
Catalog} with that amount, it would be fitting to put the money back out into the world and have other things start that might be equally interesting, in a what-goes-around-comes-around way. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
It was an unusual event, even by the standards set several decades later during the height of the Internet boom. In the vernacular of the era, it was an out-of-sight party. The Exploratorium provided optical gadgets and illusions, and there were music, dancing, food, and drink. {\i
Whole Earth Catalog} supporters from all over the country showed up, more than one thousand people in total. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
No one told the audience what was afoot until a staffer named Scott Beach took the stage at midnight and said, \uc1\u8220"Sorry to stop the volleyball and the inhaling of nitrous oxide from balloons, but there is $20,000 that is about to be handed out to the audience.\uc1\u8221" He paused and added, \uc1\u8220"Oh, I see we have your attention.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Brand had a hypothesis that, under duress, people would come up with the most amazing ideas. It didn\uc1\u8217't work out that way. Later, he concluded that, rather, under duress people would come up with remarkably stupid ideas.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Brand himself now climbed onstage and said, \uc1\u8220"I can tell you from working around foundations for three years that they are absolutely strung out about how to use money. They don\uc1\u8217't know. If we don\uc1\u8217't know, we can\uc1\u8217't really complain about them. So we are into frontier territory here. And like on any other frontier we have got to get together and deal with our problem. It may be a creative problem, and that\uc1\u8217's our task\uc2\u8212--to find a creative way out of it.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
A microphone was set up in the audience, the one-inch-thick envelope of hundred-dollar bills was handed to the crowd, and people started walking up to the mike, taking the envelope, stating what they thought should be done with the money and then handing it to the next person. Brand was dressed in an odd monk\uc1\u8217's black robe that had belonged to his father, a gesture that was meant as a gentle homage. He stood at a blackboard and began writing down the proposals as people made them in two-to four-word summaries. The hour kept getting later and people kept getting more and more raucous.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
It turned out that the assembly had a lot of what Brand thought of as knee-jerk liberal ideas. One guy stood up and said, \uc1\u8220"Let\uc1\u8217's give the money back to the Indians.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
That prompted Brand\uc1\u8217's wife, Lois, to go to the microphone and say, \uc1\u8220"I\uc1\u8217'm an Indian and I don\uc1\u8217't want the money.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
At one point someone said, \uc1\u8220"This shouldn\uc1\u8217't be decided by one chunk. There are a lot of things that can be done with this money. Let\uc1\u8217's all decide.\uc1\u8221" And then he grabbed a handful and started handing it out into the crowd.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Brand rushed back to the mike and said: \uc1\u8220"Hey, I think it is more interesting to talk about what to do with $20,000 than what to do with $100. Maybe the money will flow back to the stage.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
And miraculously, the money did come back\uc2\u8212--at least $15,000 of it. The rest disappeared into the night.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
In the end, the evening would be Fred Moore\uc1\u8217's shining moment. He had just returned from a trip to Mexico, and he was deeply involved in a project he had created called \uc1\u8220"Skool Resistance,\uc1\u8221" which had grown from his draft resistance organizing in high schools as well as from some of the deschooling ideas of Ivan Illich, the radical Chilean educator. Moore, who was almost totally broke and living in a garage in a house on the Midpeninsula, had gotten a ride to the city and arrived that evening with two dollars in his pocket.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
But after midnight, when the dispersal of the money was being debated, Moore got angry. This was just like all the bad things that money did everywhere else in the world, he decided. Early on he had gone up to the microphone, removed one of the dollar bills from his pocket, held it up in the air, and burned it. It was a little bit like the Yippies Jerry Rubin and Abbie Hoffman showering dollars onto the floor of the New York Stock Exchange. The point, he argued, was not about money, it was about people. He could see that the money that he so despised was being greeted as a savior and that people were being bought, which was typical. There were big arguments, and it was just the usual downer.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
The argument continued, and the hour grew later and later. People began leaving, and nobody seemed to have any idea that would foster anything like a group consensus. Out on the floor, Fred Moore kept talking to people about his idea of helping people directly by sharing information. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He went up to the microphone again and tried to make his point: \uc1\u8220"Now what almost happened with this young person here, who I don\uc1\u8217't know, he started to talk about a project that he wants to do in which he didn\uc1\u8217't want money for. He wanted help; he wanted to get together with others. And people yelled that was out of order\uc3\u8230.... Actually, for a moment there we were almost getting down to it. If we are going to build a change\uc2\u8212--in a changing new world, or whatever we want to call it, \uc1\u8216'new age,\uc1\u8217' then it\uc1\u8217's going to be because we are going to work together and we are going to help each other.\uc1\u8221"{\super
{\ul
11}}}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
There it was. Out of Moore\uc1\u8217's frustration with money he was developing a clear idea of how you might go about building alternative institutions. Call it Fred Moore\uc1\u8217's No Money Theory of Economics. Although no one realized it at the time, several years later it would become the heart of his initiative to build a computer club to share resources and information freely. It was to lead to one of Silicon Valley\uc1\u8217's supreme ironies: That an itinerant activist who rejected material wealth as an end in itself ended up lighting the spark of what became the \uc1\u8220"largest legal accumulation of capital in the twentieth century: the PC industry,\uc1\u8221" as venture capitalist John Doerr labeled it. Indeed Moore would also become the unrecognized patron saint of the open-source software movement, which in turn has become a major force in the computer industry.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
That evening, however, it was well past midnight and still no decision was reached. Someone finally stood up at the microphone and read the {\i
I Ching}, which decreed, \uc1\u8220"Undertakings bring misfortune.\uc1\u8221" Not a good omen. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Finally, there was a vote, just on the question of saving the money versus spending it. But it ended up solving nothing. To shrieks and general pandemonium, the vote ended in a 44\uc1\u8211-44 tie.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Moore stood up again and to applause said: \uc1\u8220"And I would like again to make my unpopular point\uc2\u8212--that why do we have to vote to divide this group? Why do you all believe in voting so much? Voting is not the best way to make decisions.\uc1\u8221" }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
He kept talking, arguing that the people are more important than the rules and that people shouldn\uc1\u8217't be the pawns of money, but the other way around.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
\uc1\u8220"I would like to suggest that some of us want to get to know each other and maybe write down our names and stick together and not necessarily think that everything just fragmented,\uc1\u8221" he said, adding that he had begun working on a manifesto that might serve as a framework for an ongoing group that would decide what to do with the money. It began: \uc1\u8220"We feel that the beginning of a union of people here tonight is more important than letting a sum of money divide us.\uc1\u8221"}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
And that\uc1\u8217's the way it would end. It was almost dawn, and the Demise Party had agreed to give the money to Fred Moore, with the idea that he would become the steward of the envelope. Stewart Brand just shook his head. It had been an interesting experiment, but he never really expected to see Moore again. {\i
Maybe he\uc1\u8217'll send a postcard from Mexico,} Brand thought as he left the Exploratorium. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Brand had found a way to get out from under the {\i
Whole Earth Catalog,} to walk away from it while he still had his sanity. For Fred Moore, however, it was like Frodo and the ring, a chapter right out of Tolkien: the ring brought power, but it was impossible to control it. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
In the days that followed, Moore felt trapped by all this newfound power and its potential and just froze up. To him, banks were part of the problem, and so not knowing what else to do with the money, he went home and put it in a tin can and went outside in his backyard and buried it.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Word of the strange conclusion to the Demise Party spread quickly. After several newspaper accounts appeared, Moore was besieged with financial requests both by phone and mail.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
And like Frodo\uc1\u8217's ring, the money wouldn\uc1\u8217't stay in the ground.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
Despite his views on the institutions that controlled money, Moore was soon forcibly turned into a \uc1\u8220"people\uc1\u8217's banker\uc1\u8221" when a small group of San Francisco activists who were engaged in building a collective in a warehouse in a tattered neighborhood south of Market Street heard about the windfall. Project One was a single site that encompassed a diverse set of community political projects, ranging from education to organizing to theater to one of the first community time-sharing computer efforts, which was called Resource One and had become the final resting place for Doug Engelbart\uc1\u8217's SDS-940. Pam Hart, a charismatic Berkeley computer-science graduate student and activist who had been one of its cofounders, had talked the Transamerica Leasing Corporation into donating the machine. Ultimately, the project gave rise to Community Memory, a Berkeley computerized information network that lasted in several different forms into the 1980s. }{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
A few Project One representatives decided to drive to Moore\uc1\u8217's home in order to make sure that the right thing was done with the money. They arrived one night and forcibly accompanied him out into the backyard, where he grudgingly dug up his tin can. In the end, Sherry Reson, one of the Project One people, was struck by the agony that was etched into his features over the decision about what to do with the money. She felt Moore was about to break down in tears as he walked out into the backyard to retrieve the can.}{\par \pard \hyphpar 	
As uncomfortable as Moore was with the realities of capitalist economics, the Demise Party had propelled him on a quest for an information network to tie all of the community and political activists together. It proved to be a crucial step toward the world of personal computing. As unlikely as it would seem, outside of the computing mainstream, politics and community were converging with technology to create a computing renaissance in the world that was to become Silicon Valley.}
